I hadn't been here in three years, and in that time the Bronx Beer Hall had changed significantly. The prices are MUCH higher than they used to be, and they are not clearly marked on the menus. In fact, the staff seem very reluctant to tell you how much the beer will cost and try to steer you toward higher-priced options. The beer is just okay. And honestly not worth the price. The setting (the indoor market in Belmont) is so-so and the staff are very slow, so there's little incentive to go here with better options opening or already opened in the Bronx. Even in Belmont there are better places (atmosphere, staff, etc.) with better beer and the same or better prices. While this was once a novel option in the Little Italy/Fordham-Rose Hill area, it's past its prime. Time to move on.

Unfortunately our waiter did not know a thing about the beer that was being served, so we took a chance ordering a cask beer and a Captain Lawrence beer, figuring can't go wrong with that choice.  I've learned that cask beers need special handling and go flat very quickly. Our cask beer arrived and was completely flat, not even a hint of carbonation. We inquired, but our waiter had no info, so he had to bring the manager over, who proceeded to try to tell us that, "all cask beers are completely flat and this was totally normal".  Unbeknownst to us, the Capt. Lawrence beer was a "sour beer", and it was exactly that and and from my taste bud's perspective - not very good.  So 2 beers - both very disappointing.  Fortunately, the manager took them both off our bill, after we had to ask what happened to the sandwiches we'ed ordered - which took close to 45 minutes to arrive at our table.  Overall, quite disappointing.

A Wonderful local brew pub, with a selection of 5 great NY beers, changed regularly, a very nice wine selection, and a menu of varied food selections from the market itself. Come for a draft or a glass, while you can also walk the market and buy some excellent meats, produce and great italian foods - pasta, olives, cheeses, oils & more. Then relax and have some stimulating conversations with patrons who come from all over the city and with the proprietors - the brothers Ramirez, two smart, and incredibly savvy young men who have a love of the Bronx and its history, far beyond their years - Anthony and Paul welcome all with a vibrancy and "neighborliness" that recalls the best of The Bronx - a can't miss spot !
